    Introduction

    In this Lab Step, you'll learn how to update and edit a manifest file to create a new ConfigMap resource within the cluster. ConfigMaps allow you to decouple configuration artifacts from image content to keep containerized applications portable. In this scenario a ConfigMap will be used to store the NGINX web server configuration externally from the NGINX container image - allowing it to be passed in at launch time. 

    Instructions

    1. Change into the k8s directory and list out its contents. In the terminal execute the following command:

    cd ../k8s && ls -la

    2. Within the Explorer view, navigate to and open the lab/code/App/lab-code/k8s/nginx.configmap.yaml manifest file.

    Take sometime to review and understand the design and intent of the nginx.configmap.yaml manifest file - which will be used to create a new ConfigMap cluster resource:

    3. Edit and update the nginx.configmap.yaml manifest file by adding the following directly beneath the #Code1.0 comment block:

    #CODE1.0:
    #add the nginx.conf configuration - this will be referenced within the deployment.yaml
    server {
     listen 80;
     server_name localhost;

     location / {
       proxy_pass http://localhost:5000/;
       proxy_set_header Host "localhost";
     }
    }

    This provides the configuration that the NGINX web server will use at runtime. The configuration is stored within a ConfigMap cluster resource and is mounted into the container when the container is launched.

    Notes:

    • Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated nginx.configmap.yaml file BEFORE proceeding onto the next step - this is very important!!
    • Make sure that the indentation is maintained
    • Consider copying the content directly from the provided version found in the equivalent solution-code directory: lab/code/App/solution-code/k8s/nginx.configmap.yaml

    The updated file nginx.configmap.yaml manifest file should now look like the following:

    4. Apply the updated nginx.configmap.yaml file into the K8s cluster - this will create a new ConfigMap resource. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl apply -f nginx.configmap.yaml

    5. List out all of the ConfigMap resourses in the K8s cluster. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get configmaps

     

    Summary

    In this Lab Step, you updated, saved, and applied the nginx.configmap.yaml manifest file into the K8s cluster. This created a new ConfigMap which contained the NGINX configuration to be mounted into the NGINX container when it is launched in the following Lab Steps.
